         <entry xml:id="zeta-dlgenr"
                xml:lang="en"
                type="mainEntry"
                prev="#hognesin-ys"
                next="#time-dlgenr"
                source="Genesis Rabbah">
            <form type="lemma" opt="false">
               <orth type="lemma" xml:lang="jpa" opt="false" select="true">זיטא</orth>
               <orth type="transliteration" xml:lang="fjb" opt="false">zyṭʾ</orth>
               <pron notation="rabbinic" opt="false">zeṭaʾ</pron>
               <gramGrp opt="false">
                  <gram type="pos" opt="false">noun</gram>
                  <gram type="gen" opt="false">f</gram>
               </gramGrp>
            </form>
            <sense xml:id="zeta-dlgenr-1" opt="false">
               <usg type="domain" opt="false">numerals/letters</usg>
               <usg type="socioCultural" norm="borrowing" opt="false">code-switching/core borrowing</usg>
               <usg type="normativity" opt="false">ad-hoc usage</usg>
               <usg type="meaningType" opt="false">lit.</usg>
               <usg type="frequency" opt="false">hapax legomenon</usg>
               <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en" subtype="sense">
                  <quote>letter ‘zeta’ (numerical value 7)</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="translationEquivalent" xml:lang="grc">
                  <usg opt="false">
                     <lang opt="false">Ancient Greek+</lang>
                  </usg>
                  <quote>ζῆτα</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="example">
                  <quote xml:lang="jpa">
אמר להון מדידכון אנא ממטי לכון זיטא
                  </quote>
                  <bibl default="false" status="draft">
                     <ref type="witness">14,2</ref>
                     <ref type="witness">I 127: 3</ref>
                  </bibl>
                  <ref type="entry">איפטה</ref>
                  <ref type="entry">איטה</ref>
                  <ref type="entry">אכטו</ref>
                  <cit type="translation">
                     <quote xml:lang="en">
                        He replied to them: From your own [language] I will prove it to you: “Zeṭaʾ (live) epṭah (seven), eṭah (go) akṭo (eight)” (Freedman / Simon I: 112)
            </quote>
                  </cit>
               </cit>
               <cit type="example">
                  <quote xml:lang="jpa">
אמר להון מדידכון אנה ממטי לכון זיטא
                  </quote>
                  <bibl default="false" status="draft">
                     <ref type="witness">20,6</ref>
                     <ref type="witness">I 189: 3</ref>
                  </bibl>
                  <ref type="entry">איפטה</ref>
                  <ref type="entry">היטה</ref>
                  <ref type="entry">אוקטון</ref>
                  <cit type="translation">
                     <quote xml:lang="en">He replied to them: From your own [language] I will prove
                        it to you: “Zeṭaʾ (live) epṭah (seven), eṭah (go) akṭo (eight)” (Freedman / Simon I: 164)
                     </quote>
                  </cit>
                  <note>= Yalq. Bereshit 20 (6c: 53); NumR 4,3; Yalq. Bemidbar 692 (220d: 13), Tanh Bemidbar 18, TanhB Bemidbar 21; yYev 5d: 7 (corr.): <term xml:lang="jpa">זוטא</term>
                     <term xml:lang="fjb">zwṭʾ</term></note>
               </cit>
            </sense>
            <etym type="borrowing" opt="false">
               <lbl opt="false">source language</lbl>
               <lang opt="false">Ancient Greek+</lang>
               <cit type="etymon" xml:lang="grc">
                  <xr type="related" opt="false">
                     <lbl opt="false">Cf. LSJ</lbl>
                     <ref target="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/morph?l=zh%3Dta&amp;la=greek&amp;can=zh%3Dta0"
                          type="entry">ζῆτα</ref>
                  </xr>
               </cit>
            </etym>
            <note anchored="true">
According to R. Huna a foetus which was born at 7th month is viable, 
but a foetus which was born at 8th month is not viable. R. Abbahu gives a 
mnemonic based on a Greek pun:  The name of the Greek letter ‘zeta’ 
(numerical value 7) sounds like the Greek imp. <term xml:lang="grc">ζῆτω</term> (‘let it live!’), while the name of the letter ‘eta’ (numerical value 8) sounds like the Greek <term xml:lang="grc">ἲτω</term> (‘let it go!’, i.e. ‘die!’).
   </note>
